There are North Koreans
going overseas.

00:54:48.190 --> 00:54:49.490
There's so much exchange.

00:54:49.490 --> 00:54:50.790
It's so rich.

00:54:50.790 --> 00:54:52.090
And so absolutely
there is a sense

00:54:52.090 --> 00:54:53.390
that North Korea is
extremely international.

00:54:53.390 --> 00:54:54.690
It's a proud-- yeah, proud
part of the socialist bloc

00:54:54.690 --> 00:54:55.990
and it is very much kind of up
in step with what is happening

00:54:55.990 --> 00:54:57.290
in the Soviet Union
in other countries.

00:54:57.290 --> 00:54:58.590
So, the children
that are reading

00:54:58.590 --> 00:54:59.890
or the young reading these
magazines are definitely made

00:54:59.890 --> 00:55:01.190
to see themselves as a part of a
broader, you know, a broad kind

00:55:01.190 --> 00:55:02.490
of republic of socialist
children on the world.

00:55:02.490 --> 00:55:03.790
So, yeah. Thank you.

00:55:03.790 --> 00:55:05.590
Yes.

00:55:05.590 --> 00:55:16.650
[ Inaudible ]

00:55:16.650 --> 00:55:18.860
Right. Great question.

00:55:18.860 --> 00:55:22.210
And again, you know, I'm not in
a really good place right now

00:55:22.210 --> 00:55:23.880
to be able to answer
it completely.

00:55:23.880 --> 00:55:27.230
But my understanding from
what I've seen until now,

00:55:27.230 --> 00:55:29.420
there are no private
publication.

00:55:29.420 --> 00:55:31.160
These are not commercial
enterprises.

00:55:31.160 --> 00:55:35.950
These are all public
institutions and the process

00:55:35.950 --> 00:55:39.740
of publishing, as it was
in South Korea as well,

00:55:39.740 --> 00:55:42.850
is controlled very closely
and there are censorship,

00:55:42.850 --> 00:55:45.810
there are multiple steps
in which writers have

00:55:45.810 --> 00:55:47.110
to submit their writing.

00:55:47.110 --> 00:55:51.060
And so, you know, it's I
would say non-for-profit.

00:55:51.060 --> 00:55:54.810
You know, these are magazines
that are looked at very,

00:55:54.810 --> 00:55:57.990
very closely and
are-- they're only--

00:55:57.990 --> 00:56:00.360
and they're public
or I would say kind

00:56:00.360 --> 00:56:03.170
of national publishing houses.

00:56:03.170 --> 00:56:06.030
So, you know, again
that's to say

00:56:06.030 --> 00:56:09.560
that there is very strict
censorship that is controlled,

00:56:09.560 --> 00:56:12.220
but it's also the case for
South Korea where, you know,

00:56:12.220 --> 00:56:16.370
especially with the
American military government,

00:56:16.370 --> 00:56:19.110
they watched South Korean
publications very closely

00:56:19.110 --> 00:56:21.230
to kind of smell out any sort

00:56:21.230 --> 00:56:25.240
of pro-communist kind
of, you know, tendencies.

00:56:25.240 --> 00:56:30.080
So, you know, they-- I'm
not an expert on this period

00:56:30.080 --> 00:56:33.700
of the kind of the publishing
industry as I would like to be

00:56:33.700 --> 00:56:37.540
but my sense is that, yes,
the cases that this was--

00:56:37.540 --> 00:56:39.370
there was no private publishing.

00:56:39.370 --> 00:56:41.510
Sir, in the back, did
you have a question?

00:56:41.510 --> 00:56:52.730
[ Inaudible ]

00:56:52.730 --> 00:56:54.530
Right.

00:56:54.530 --> 00:56:57.270
[ Inaudible ]

00:56:57.270 --> 00:56:59.070
Right.

00:56:59.070 --> 00:57:05.020
[ Inaudible ]

00:57:05.020 --> 00:57:07.010
Right. So, again, you
know, these are things

00:57:07.010 --> 00:57:09.060
that I think are a little
bit more difficult to gauge,

00:57:09.060 --> 00:57:12.920
barring a kind of more extensive
research on reader reception

00:57:12.920 --> 00:57:14.540
in North Korea from
the '50s to '60s.

00:57:14.540 --> 00:57:16.160
You can imagine that's a
little bit challenging.

00:57:16.160 --> 00:57:23.790
I mean my answer to that is that
we can tell to a certain extent

00:57:23.790 --> 00:57:26.390
that there is reader
participation

00:57:26.390 --> 00:57:30.240
because you get these-- in every
issue there are always reader

00:57:30.240 --> 00:57:31.820
letters that are
sent to the editor.

00:57:31.820 --> 00:57:36.590
So, you get voices from
readers and they're always--

00:57:36.590 --> 00:57:37.890
they're at-- the place--

00:57:37.890 --> 00:57:39.680
The location from which they
are writing and the name

00:57:39.680 --> 00:57:42.480
of their school and their
age is written down.

00:57:42.480 --> 00:57:43.780
So, you kind see that, oh,

00:57:43.780 --> 00:57:47.550
a lot of these magazines are
being picked up by young readers

00:57:47.550 --> 00:57:51.020
from all over the
country and so--

00:57:51.020 --> 00:57:54.500
But we don't have
circulation numbers.

00:57:54.500 --> 00:57:56.360
You know, there's not been
that kind of research done

00:57:56.360 --> 00:57:58.290
on these magazines quite yet.

00:57:58.290 --> 00:58:00.970
So, I can't say, for
certain, but the--

00:58:00.970 --> 00:58:05.430
within the magazine as I read
them, I see that they are kind

00:58:05.430 --> 00:58:09.220
of talking about the
importance that they view

00:58:09.220 --> 00:58:12.350
in as their materials as
supplementary to school.

00:58:12.350 --> 00:58:14.930
So, the sense is that
yes, there are textbooks.

00:58:14.930 --> 00:58:16.710
Yeah, the children
are in school,

00:58:16.710 --> 00:58:19.140
but these magazines
are meant to kind of--

00:58:19.140 --> 00:58:22.010
as enrichment, as
further studying.

00:58:22.010 --> 00:58:25.890
And again, with reader
letters that are embedded

00:58:25.890 --> 00:58:27.310
in these magazines,
you get a sense

00:58:27.310 --> 00:58:31.510
of how broad geographically
these readers are spread out.

00:58:31.510 --> 00:58:41.690
[ Inaudible ]

00:58:41.690 --> 00:58:46.950
Yeah. You know what, I
can't really speak now

00:58:46.950 --> 00:58:48.830
because my interest sort of--

00:58:48.830 --> 00:58:52.220
I've bracketed them at
the 1960s, but my guess--

00:58:52.220 --> 00:58:54.480
Oh, and I don't have that
image here as to that.

00:58:54.480 --> 00:58:58.110
I have a guide that I know
who is in North Korea,

00:58:58.110 --> 00:58:59.890
